00:43:33.450 --> 00:43:34.470
PAULA MADISON: Right.

00:43:34.470 --> 00:43:35.180
Great question.

00:43:35.180 --> 00:43:37.030
Tell me your name?

00:43:37.030 --> 00:43:37.700
ANNE: I'm Anne.

00:43:37.700 --> 00:43:38.780
PAULA MADISON: Anne.

00:43:38.780 --> 00:43:39.700
Thank you for that.

00:43:42.230 --> 00:43:45.880
When I was 51, I started
running marathons.

00:43:45.880 --> 00:43:47.980
I know, because I'm crazy.

00:43:47.980 --> 00:43:52.980
And I didn't know you could
train to run a marathon.

00:43:52.980 --> 00:43:54.960
I was like, oh, a coach!

00:43:54.960 --> 00:43:56.240
Really!

00:43:56.240 --> 00:43:57.690
I know how to run.

00:43:57.690 --> 00:43:58.940
Like, you just run!

00:43:58.940 --> 00:43:59.750
No, no, no.

00:43:59.750 --> 00:44:01.347
It's a different
kind of running.

00:44:01.347 --> 00:44:02.930
So my husband, who
by then had already

00:44:02.930 --> 00:44:07.460
run like 9 or 10 marathons,
is like, baby listen.

00:44:07.460 --> 00:44:10.100
He said, I've only ever
seen you run for the train.

00:44:10.100 --> 00:44:11.900
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:11.900 --> 00:44:14.160
And I said, and?

00:44:14.160 --> 00:44:16.210
He said, do you know
how long a marathon is?

00:44:16.210 --> 00:44:17.600
I said 26.2 miles.

00:44:17.600 --> 00:44:18.670
I know how long it is.

00:44:18.670 --> 00:44:21.484
He said, well, maybe you
should start with a 5k.

00:44:21.484 --> 00:44:23.150
I said, are you trying
to discourage me?

00:44:23.150 --> 00:44:24.660
No, no, no, no, no, no, no.

00:44:24.660 --> 00:44:25.740
And I said, what's a k?

00:44:25.740 --> 00:44:26.240
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:26.240 --> 00:44:26.740
Truly.

00:44:26.740 --> 00:44:28.360
That's true conversation.

00:44:28.360 --> 00:44:31.620
So I had a running partner.

00:44:31.620 --> 00:44:35.750
Who, lovely woman, one of
my dearest friends now.

00:44:35.750 --> 00:44:38.530
And she's probably 10,
12 years older than me.

00:44:38.530 --> 00:44:39.880
And she's Jewish.

00:44:39.880 --> 00:44:45.050
And while running, we talked
about all kinds of things.

00:44:45.050 --> 00:44:49.810
It's really hard to be
really mad at somebody

00:44:49.810 --> 00:44:52.190
when today is a 12 mile run.

00:44:52.190 --> 00:44:53.130
You understand?

00:44:53.130 --> 00:44:57.330
You figure out
whether it's quilting,

00:44:57.330 --> 00:45:00.900
whether it's playing
Minecraft, whatever

00:45:00.900 --> 00:45:03.880
it is that's the common
bond, and then you

00:45:03.880 --> 00:45:05.420
get beyond the superficial.

00:45:05.420 --> 00:45:08.160
Yeah we talked about cookies,
and grandchildren of course.

00:45:08.160 --> 00:45:10.350
But there would
be points where we

00:45:10.350 --> 00:45:15.220
got into some really meaningful,
serious, and potentially

00:45:15.220 --> 00:45:16.970
dangerous discussions.

00:45:16.970 --> 00:45:21.380
But we had enough trust in each
other to know that this is not

00:45:21.380 --> 00:45:23.930
cocktail party banter.

00:45:23.930 --> 00:45:28.420
And she is one of my
dearest, and closest friends.

00:45:28.420 --> 00:45:30.150
It's hard not to be
friends with somebody

00:45:30.150 --> 00:45:31.570
who you're sweating on.

00:45:31.570 --> 00:45:33.610
Well, I think.

00:45:33.610 --> 00:45:37.010
But anyway, you get my--
it can't be sitting across

00:45:37.010 --> 00:45:40.870
from each other at work, where
we both have a bottle of water,

00:45:40.870 --> 00:45:44.660
and I want to talk
to you about-- that's

00:45:44.660 --> 00:45:46.910
too- it's too focused.

00:45:46.910 --> 00:45:47.870
It's too whatever.

00:45:47.870 --> 00:45:50.464
And in an environment
like this, quite honestly,

00:45:50.464 --> 00:45:52.130
the best way to have
these conversations

00:45:52.130 --> 00:45:53.540
is to have them moderated.

00:45:53.540 --> 00:45:54.560
Or brokered.

00:45:54.560 --> 00:45:56.150
Have somebody who
really does know

00:45:56.150 --> 00:46:00.860
how to encourage the
discussion, and can

00:46:00.860 --> 00:46:05.290
tell when it may be
getting-- So talk about what

00:46:05.290 --> 00:46:09.200
you meant by that, as opposed
to, what did you mean by that?

00:46:09.200 --> 00:46:10.270
You know?

00:46:10.270 --> 00:46:11.510
Yeah.

00:46:11.510 --> 00:46:13.019
Yes.

00:46:13.019 --> 00:46:15.060
AUDIENCE: So that was a
really interesting point.

00:46:15.060 --> 00:46:17.351
And you're talking about
having a moderator in a group.

00:46:17.351 --> 00:46:20.050
But how can you kind of
organically facilitate that?

00:46:20.050 --> 00:46:23.854
Because my assumption, and this
I guess, is a generalization,

00:46:23.854 --> 00:46:25.270
is that the people
who are already

00:46:25.270 --> 00:46:27.520
somewhat interested
in that already,

00:46:27.520 --> 00:46:28.910
are the ones who attend.

00:46:28.910 --> 00:46:29.410
Right?

00:46:29.410 --> 00:46:31.940
And so we don't need
a homogeneous group

00:46:31.940 --> 00:46:33.989
to consistently have
this conversation.

00:46:33.989 --> 00:46:36.530
You kind of want to spread it
to the group that maybe doesn't

00:46:36.530 --> 00:46:37.850
have any interest in attending.

00:46:37.850 --> 00:46:39.680
So how do you have that
organically happen,

00:46:39.680 --> 00:46:42.312
without forcing someone to go
to a round table or something?

00:46:42.312 --> 00:46:44.020
PAULA MADISON: Right,
I don't believe you

00:46:44.020 --> 00:46:46.571
can have it happen organically.

00:46:46.571 --> 00:46:47.820
AUDIENCE: You cannot have it--

00:46:47.820 --> 00:46:49.819
PAULA MADISON: I don't
think you can organically

00:46:49.819 --> 00:46:53.300
have people say, today,
let's talk about scary issue

00:46:53.300 --> 00:46:57.020
about-- I don't think that
organically, that can happen.

00:46:57.020 --> 00:46:59.160
I think that it has
to be purposeful.

00:46:59.160 --> 00:47:01.820
I think that there has
to be a decision made,

00:47:01.820 --> 00:47:03.840
somewhere along the line.

00:47:03.840 --> 00:47:05.840
Whether it comes out of
HR, whether it comes out

00:47:05.840 --> 00:47:08.350
of a management group, whether
it comes out of somewhere.

00:47:08.350 --> 00:47:12.850
But somebody who
says, look, this

00:47:12.850 --> 00:47:14.140
is my first time at Google.

00:47:14.140 --> 00:47:16.470
The only person I know
at Google is Laura.

00:47:16.470 --> 00:47:19.060
And maybe some of you now.

00:47:19.060 --> 00:47:23.070
But if this is an
environment where

00:47:23.070 --> 00:47:27.620
you get your clothes cleaned,
you get your laundry done.

00:47:27.620 --> 00:47:30.050
I don't even know what
else you all get for free.

00:47:30.050 --> 00:47:32.630
[LAUGHTER] But if
it's designed to

00:47:32.630 --> 00:47:39.290
enrich-- if it's designed
to smooth and tamp down

00:47:39.290 --> 00:47:43.700
distractions, so you can have
an enriched, more effective

00:47:43.700 --> 00:47:47.710
and efficient
experience here, look

00:47:47.710 --> 00:47:50.940
at what you're not discussing.

00:47:50.940 --> 00:47:55.870
Look at what is not
being discussed at all.

00:47:55.870 --> 00:48:02.170
And how much more risk, and
it is risky, no question.

00:48:02.170 --> 00:48:04.710
When I was at NBC Universal,
we brought everybody together,

00:48:04.710 --> 00:48:08.420
on something called
NBC Unity Day.

00:48:08.420 --> 00:48:10.950
And we dealt with a
lot of these things,

00:48:10.950 --> 00:48:12.840
with the blessing
and the encouragement

00:48:12.840 --> 00:48:14.890
of the tip-top most management.

00:48:14.890 --> 00:48:19.410
Because you can't just make
this up, and say, so now,

00:48:19.410 --> 00:48:21.240
every Wednesday we're
going to gather.

00:48:21.240 --> 00:48:24.050
Because without it
being moderated,

00:48:24.050 --> 00:48:25.390
it could get real dicey.

00:48:29.260 --> 00:48:33.710
So the premise of organic, I
don't think it can be organic.

00:48:33.710 --> 00:48:34.502
Not at work.

00:48:34.502 --> 00:48:36.460
MAR JAYE: I actually have
an alternative there.

00:48:36.460 --> 00:48:37.140
My name's Mar Jaye.

00:48:37.140 --> 00:48:39.098
Thank you so much for
coming Miss Madison, that

00:48:39.098 --> 00:48:40.450
was an incredible lecture.

00:48:40.450 --> 00:48:45.260
But we do have a Group here
that was created organically,

00:48:45.260 --> 00:48:48.090
in some way, called
Equality Working Group.

00:48:48.090 --> 00:48:50.370
So if you go to your
internal Google Group,

00:48:50.370 --> 00:48:56.580
and look that alias up,
we have monthly lunches.

00:48:56.580 --> 00:49:00.190
Where people of all
types from Google,

00:49:00.190 --> 00:49:01.810
we come together and have lunch.

00:49:01.810 --> 00:49:03.590
And it's really
great, because you're

00:49:03.590 --> 00:49:06.450
engaging with people who you
would probably never talk to.

00:49:06.450 --> 00:49:11.680
Because a lot of us, we
silo ourselves in every way,

00:49:11.680 --> 00:49:15.030
with people who look like us, or
talk like us, or think like us.

00:49:15.030 --> 00:49:18.620
So it's a really cool
way for different people

00:49:18.620 --> 00:49:20.070
to get together, to engage.

00:49:20.070 --> 00:49:25.000
And we talk a lot about
race, and gender issues,

00:49:25.000 --> 00:49:26.160
and things like that.

00:49:26.160 --> 00:49:28.070
I mean people ask questions.

00:49:28.070 --> 00:49:32.030
They're like, well why does
a black person feel this way?

00:49:32.030 --> 00:49:34.560
They just don't
know, and they need

00:49:34.560 --> 00:49:37.680
some help to kind of
understand and walk

00:49:37.680 --> 00:49:39.817
through someone else's
shoes to understand that.

00:49:39.817 --> 00:49:42.400
And so we put ourselves in this
really safe environment, where

00:49:42.400 --> 00:49:43.750
we can do this here at Google.

00:49:43.750 --> 00:49:46.220
So I would encourage you guys
to look up the Working Group

00:49:46.220 --> 00:49:47.262
and come have lunch.

00:49:47.262 --> 00:49:48.720
PAULA MADISON: I
think that's great

00:49:48.720 --> 00:49:51.290
if you all have been
able to come together,

00:49:51.290 --> 00:49:56.320
and pretty much-- maybe, I
don't know what the word-- but

00:49:56.320 --> 00:49:58.170
leave any kind of
hostility that could

00:49:58.170 --> 00:49:59.870
come from that at the door.

00:49:59.870 --> 00:50:04.890
My experience is that, it
can get there really quickly,

00:50:04.890 --> 00:50:06.870
if not.

00:50:06.870 --> 00:50:09.710
But if what you all have done
is create that environment,

00:50:09.710 --> 00:50:11.025
I applaud you.

00:50:11.025 --> 00:50:12.150
Because that's spectacular.

00:50:12.150 --> 00:50:14.080
That's a rare thing to happen.

00:50:14.080 --> 00:50:18.354
So maybe free lunches and free
cleaning does make you nicer.

00:50:18.354 --> 00:50:19.340
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:19.340 --> 00:50:20.140
MAR JAYE: Yeah.

00:50:20.140 --> 00:50:21.850
And I think the
great thing here is

00:50:21.850 --> 00:50:24.395
that, like you were saying,
how do we bring people?

00:50:24.395 --> 00:50:27.730
Because you're right, people
come who are naturally,

00:50:27.730 --> 00:50:29.384
they want to engage in this way.

00:50:29.384 --> 00:50:31.550
But there's a lot of people
who probably don't come,

00:50:31.550 --> 00:50:35.010
because they're in
exact opposite feeling.

00:50:35.010 --> 00:50:36.950
So we encourage everyone
to bring somebody

00:50:36.950 --> 00:50:39.050
you know, who would
never come to this,

00:50:39.050 --> 00:50:42.810
If you weren't their friend,
and encourage them to.

00:50:42.810 --> 00:50:44.810
PAULA MADISON: You should
be applauded for that.

00:50:44.810 --> 00:50:46.770
I don't know if you all have
like in-house communications.

00:50:46.770 --> 00:50:48.228
Tell me how much
more time we have?

00:50:48.228 --> 00:50:50.360
I don't know if you have
in-house communications,

00:50:50.360 --> 00:50:52.890
but maybe you can let people
know that that happens.

00:50:52.890 --> 00:50:56.610
Because that, I think,
is a game changer.

00:50:56.610 --> 00:51:03.340
Having worked in so many places,
and in so many different roles

00:51:03.340 --> 00:51:04.400
throughout my life.

00:51:04.400 --> 00:51:08.300
What I have found
is that, it's tough.

00:51:08.300 --> 00:51:13.650
It's real, and people, it gets
sometimes stuck right here.

00:51:13.650 --> 00:51:15.390
Oh, so I do have
one more anecdote.

00:51:15.390 --> 00:51:17.720
And again, I'm sorry all my
anecdotes involve violence.

