I apologize.

00:51:18.886 --> 00:51:21.020
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:21.020 --> 00:51:24.250
When I was in college,
which was many moons ago,

00:51:24.250 --> 00:51:31.290
there was a an African American
student, and a white student.

00:51:31.290 --> 00:51:33.460
And they both lived in
the same dorm, both women.

00:51:33.460 --> 00:51:35.626
And the white student said
to the African American--

00:51:35.626 --> 00:51:38.560
and they were in the
bathroom-- and she

00:51:38.560 --> 00:51:41.370
said, can I touch your hair?

00:51:41.370 --> 00:51:43.830
And the black student said no.

00:51:43.830 --> 00:51:46.650
And the white student said, no,
but I just want to touch it.

00:51:46.650 --> 00:51:49.960
And the black student
said, don't touch my hair.

00:51:49.960 --> 00:51:53.580
She actually was trimming
her afro at the time.

00:51:53.580 --> 00:51:55.810
The white student reached
out, and touched her hair.

00:51:55.810 --> 00:51:57.726
And the black student
stabbed her in the hand.

00:52:01.020 --> 00:52:02.330
Right?

00:52:02.330 --> 00:52:05.610
So what I'm getting
at is, what may

00:52:05.610 --> 00:52:10.170
be comfortable for some people,
like-- So with my friend,

00:52:10.170 --> 00:52:12.850
my marathon partner, we would
have conversations about stuff,

00:52:12.850 --> 00:52:14.641
and I'd say, you know
can't be just talking

00:52:14.641 --> 00:52:17.080
to every black person
about this, right?

00:52:17.080 --> 00:52:19.629
You've got to go slowly.

00:52:19.629 --> 00:52:21.170
But don't be walking
up to people who

00:52:21.170 --> 00:52:23.240
you barely know, and say hey!

00:52:23.240 --> 00:52:25.560
Because it could go very wrong.

00:52:25.560 --> 00:52:27.270
So that's what I'm saying.

00:52:27.270 --> 00:52:28.970
You all have created
an environment

00:52:28.970 --> 00:52:33.820
in your group, where
there are ground rules.

00:52:33.820 --> 00:52:37.160
And there are people around
who could serve as referees,

00:52:37.160 --> 00:52:39.220
and moderators, who
are inside the group.

00:52:39.220 --> 00:52:42.970
Because somehow you all
have come to an agreement,

00:52:42.970 --> 00:52:45.530
that this is how we're all
going to conduct ourselves.

00:52:45.530 --> 00:52:46.910
Which I applaud you for.

00:52:46.910 --> 00:52:48.042
I think that's spectacular.

00:52:48.042 --> 00:52:48.750
MAR JAYE: Thanks.

00:52:48.750 --> 00:52:50.290
And I did want to give
one more anecdote,

00:52:50.290 --> 00:52:51.850
because I think it's
something that--

00:52:51.850 --> 00:52:54.120
PAULA MADISON: Does
yours involve violence?

00:52:54.120 --> 00:52:57.297
MAR JAYE: It involves
racism in the workplace.

00:52:57.297 --> 00:52:58.130
I had an experience.

00:52:58.130 --> 00:53:00.490
I work in advertising
here at Google,

00:53:00.490 --> 00:53:03.610
and I talk on the phone
with companies a lot.

00:53:03.610 --> 00:53:06.330
And marketing reps, and things.

00:53:06.330 --> 00:53:11.540
I was confused for,
I guess the person

00:53:11.540 --> 00:53:14.390
I was talking to thought
I was a white person.

00:53:14.390 --> 00:53:17.290
And this happened twice, in
my five years here at Google.

00:53:17.290 --> 00:53:20.370
And they started to
say something racist.

00:53:20.370 --> 00:53:24.040
What the first call was, about
Muslims, and then the other one

00:53:24.040 --> 00:53:25.730
was about black people.

00:53:25.730 --> 00:53:27.730
They assuming I was white.

00:53:27.730 --> 00:53:33.640
So I really encourage people
to be allies to all races,

00:53:33.640 --> 00:53:36.350
because that was the
first time in my life

00:53:36.350 --> 00:53:42.650
I was able to actually
fight and support

00:53:42.650 --> 00:53:44.320
a minority, being a minority.

00:53:44.320 --> 00:53:45.500
That doesn't happen to me.

00:53:45.500 --> 00:53:51.150
But in this unique situation, I
had the power to actually say,

00:53:51.150 --> 00:53:52.550
well that's not right.

00:53:52.550 --> 00:53:54.810
Because here they are,
thinking I'm white.

00:53:54.810 --> 00:53:58.070
And so when you are
speaking with your peers,

00:53:58.070 --> 00:54:00.790
you have a lot more power
to change the narrative

00:54:00.790 --> 00:54:04.270
than you do when you are usually
the one that's disenfranchised.

00:54:04.270 --> 00:54:08.170
Because a lot of times it goes
out one ear, and out the other

00:54:08.170 --> 00:54:11.000
when you're the person
being disenfranchised,

00:54:11.000 --> 00:54:15.160
speaking about your situation.

00:54:15.160 --> 00:54:19.220
So I really encourage allies of
everyone to really speak out.

00:54:19.220 --> 00:54:22.540
Because it actually gets
through deeper than I think

00:54:22.540 --> 00:54:24.099
it might otherwise.

00:54:24.099 --> 00:54:25.640
PAULA MADISON: And
I have a question.

00:54:25.640 --> 00:54:28.210
Did you tell-- In
the situation where

00:54:28.210 --> 00:54:32.560
it was something, racist
towards black people,

00:54:32.560 --> 00:54:34.250
did you tell the
person you were black?

00:54:34.250 --> 00:54:35.500
MAR JAYE: No.

00:54:35.500 --> 00:54:38.080
I didn't.

00:54:38.080 --> 00:54:41.490
Because he felt bad when
I actually was speaking

00:54:41.490 --> 00:54:44.280
in support of black people.

00:54:44.280 --> 00:54:47.080
So it took for him.

00:54:47.080 --> 00:54:49.280
He was like, oh
well, I guess maybe

00:54:49.280 --> 00:54:50.655
I didn't think of
it in that way.

00:54:50.655 --> 00:54:52.196
PAULA MADISON: So
you think you think

00:54:52.196 --> 00:54:54.446
it was more effective for
him to think you were white.

00:54:54.446 --> 00:54:56.612
MAR JAYE: Yeah I think it
was more effective for him

00:54:56.612 --> 00:54:58.040
to continue to
think I was white.

00:54:58.040 --> 00:55:00.862
And then my manager told me
to never talk to him again.

00:55:00.862 --> 00:55:01.710
[LAUGHING]

00:55:01.710 --> 00:55:02.310
PAULA MADISON: That's
tough when you're

00:55:02.310 --> 00:55:03.560
doing business with people.

00:55:03.560 --> 00:55:05.990
I mean sometimes, you
don't have that option.

00:55:05.990 --> 00:55:07.130
But I appreciate it.

00:55:07.130 --> 00:55:08.300
Well thank you very much.

00:55:08.300 --> 00:55:10.400
Thank you for that.

00:55:10.400 --> 00:55:12.580
So that actually was
the last question.

00:55:12.580 --> 00:55:17.890
I should tell you that, so
I'll be back there in a minute

00:55:17.890 --> 00:55:21.870
if you are interested in
the book, which is very

00:55:21.870 --> 00:55:23.340
multilayered and multifaceted.

00:55:23.340 --> 00:55:29.030
And by the way, at the very
end of it, we went to China

00:55:29.030 --> 00:55:32.830
and 300 of my grandfather's
direct descendants

00:55:32.830 --> 00:55:35.545
welcomed the 20 of us black
Chinese into the family.

00:55:40.800 --> 00:55:44.460
We have a long documented
legacy in my family

00:55:44.460 --> 00:55:45.710
on the Chinese side.

00:55:45.710 --> 00:55:50.090
I'm actually the 151st
generation of the Lowe clan.

00:55:50.090 --> 00:55:56.320
And my family's documented
history goes back to 1,006 B.C.

00:55:56.320 --> 00:56:01.450
And yet, on my
African Jamaican side,

00:56:01.450 --> 00:56:06.330
I can't find documents
past grandparents.

00:56:06.330 --> 00:56:08.220
But having said all
that, I would just

00:56:08.220 --> 00:56:10.470
like for you to understand,
that while I talked

00:56:10.470 --> 00:56:13.950
about my documented lineage,
my undocumented lineage

00:56:13.950 --> 00:56:15.590
goes back farther than that.

00:56:15.590 --> 00:56:19.240
Because the first man
and woman were African.

00:56:19.240 --> 00:56:21.950
In fact, so we all came
from that continent.

00:56:21.950 --> 00:56:25.450
So I just like to put into
perspective that while, oh yay,

00:56:25.450 --> 00:56:30.840
I can look up the people in
my family for many, many years

00:56:30.840 --> 00:56:38.140
back in our zupu, but the start
of mankind began in Africa.

00:56:38.140 --> 00:56:40.020
So with that, I
thank you very much.

00:56:40.020 --> 00:56:42.134
Thank you for having me.

00:56:42.134 --> 00:56:43.090
[APPLAUSE]

00:56:43.090 --> 00:56:46.069
And thank you, Laura,
for inviting me.

00:56:46.069 --> 00:56:47.110
My little intern grew up!

00:56:47.110 --> 00:56:48.660
Yay!

